A 'coho' refers to a type of fish that belongs to the salmon family. It is also known as silver salmon. 
Cohos typically have a silvery-blue color on their back and a white or cream-colored belly. 
They have a streamlined body shape, with a forked tail and small black spots on their back. 
Their scales are relatively small and smooth to the touch. 
Cohos are typically found in the northern Pacific Ocean, as well as in rivers and streams along the Pacific coast. 
They are commonly sought-after by anglers for both sport and commercial fishing purposes. 
Cohos are also an important food source for both humans and animals in many parts of the world.
